But the worst part is, they try to make Muhammad out to be this perfect man, humble and wise. But history says somethin' different. I gotta wonder if Muslims today even know the real story about how Muhammad got so powerful.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'.  You see, the way folks been talkin' 'bout Jesus these days ain't nothin' like what he was really preachin'. It's like they got off track, ya know?  Seems like the world's gettin' more open-minded,  makin' progress and all that.  But you still got those old-timers, stuck in their ways,  refusin' to budge.  But they ain't gonna change nothin'. 

Now, I reckon folks are gonna start thinkin' 'bout the real Jesus, what he truly meant. They're gonna want to peel back all the layers of stuff that got added over the years. It might take a while, maybe even a long time, but it'll happen.  We're talkin' a whole turnaround, like turnin' back the clock.

Folks are gonna start followin' Jesus like it's the good old days, just his words, nothin' else. The church might still be there, leadin' the way, but it won't be the same.  Everyone's gonna be thinkin' alike, with the same beliefs and doin' things the same way.  

History's full of these big changes. Remember when Christians were gettin' persecuted by the Romans?  Then they turned around and became Christians themselves!  Same thing happened here in our country, went from slavery to black folks leadin' the way. 

This whole thing, it's gonna happen in the church too, goin' back to the roots, forgettin' all the extra stuff. And it's gonna be like readin' Jesus' words in a new way, not takin' everything so literally.

So, what happened since Jesus walked the earth?  Well, it all started with Judaism, the foundation of Christianity.  They believed in only one God, had their scriptures, the whole shebang.  But even then, they weren't all on the same page, split into different groups, like the Sadducees, Pharisees, and those crazy Zealots.

Look, I reckon "The Jungle" shows folks are pretty darn greedy, you know? Deep down, they just wanna look out for number one, make their own lives easier, and don't give a hoot about nobody else, especially not the little guy. The book makes that plain as day. 

Take them factory owners and bosses, for instance. All they care about is makin' their factories big and fancy, makin' as much dough as they can. They don't give a lick about anyone gettin' hurt or messed up along the way.

Upton Sinclair, he writes about how the factories are like these big, ugly beasts, all black and smokin', spewin' out pollution like it's nothin'. He's tryin' to show how these factory owners just don't care about the people or the animals, just about makin' money. They don't care about the smoke chokin' the air or the mess they're makin' with all the animal waste runnin' around.

And the bosses, they don't care about their workers neither. They'll squeeze every penny they can out of 'em, work 'em till they drop, and then lay 'em off without a second thought. Back then, there weren't no laws protectin' workers, so they could get away with anything. It was a dog-eat-dog world, and the workers were the ones gettin' eaten.

Sinclair says the workers were like slaves, treated worse than dirt. They had no say in nothin', no way to fight back. They were stuck in this awful system, workin' themselves to the bone just to survive.

Y'all ever notice how some folks try to make you feel a certain way 'bout things? Like, they wanna pump you up or make you all sad and mopey?  Well, F. Scott Fitzgerald, that fella who wrote "The Great Gatsby," he's a real master at that. He uses all sorts of tricks, like pairing words together that don't usually go together, kinda like sayin' "purple polka-dotted toaster" - it just makes ya stop and think, ya know? And he's real good at usin' symbols too, like colors.  He takes a color, gives it a meaning, then uses it again and again to make ya think of that same feelin'. 

He's got this whole thing goin' on with colors like gold, green, white, and red.  But the ones he uses the most are white and gray - 'specially white and gray.  He uses 'em to show that somethin' ain't nothin' special, like a bunch of folks all wearin' the same clothes.

See, white for Fitzgerald means somethin' kinda fancy and nice, like Daisy, she's always in white, even when she's dressin' up for Gatsby's big parties.   But gray, well, that's more like somethin' old and faded, like them big apartment buildings Nick sees in the city.  He uses these colors to show how folks are all the same, like they're parts of a big ol' machine.

Then, when Fitzgerald wants ya to think somethin' ain't important, he uses white and gray for it. He does this with Daisy, for example. After a while, when he keeps describin' her in these colors, she starts to seem less like a person and more like somethin' to be owned, like a fancy car or a piece of jewelry.

So, Fitzgerald's playin' with colors to make ya feel somethin' specific, like Daisy ain't just a woman, but somethin' more like an idea - somethin' predictable and kinda empty.

Well, lemme tell ya about this little piece of land in San Diego.  It's a real gem.  Sun's always shinin', folks grow all sorts of good eatin' there – tomatoes, citrus, you name it.  Even got folks growin' stuff organic,  they're sellin' it faster than a politician promises a tax cut!

Now, this here land, it's got a history,  been around since way back when the Native Americans lived here.  Then came the cowboys and folks cuttin' wood,  they used it for grazin' and choppin' wood.

So, I was thinkin', what if someone wanted to turn this land back into a farm,  but somethin' special,  organic and good for the critters too?  Well, it ain't gonna be cheap,  takes more work than just throwin' chemicals around.  But, there's all sorts of programs to help folks out,  like hand outs from the government.

They got this big plan for keepin' all the critters alive,  even the rare ones.  Seems like a lotta work,  plantin' all sorts of stuff to keep the animals happy,  but it's good for the land.

Now, this organic farm I found nearby,  they're doin' it right.  They're makin' money and keepin' the wildlife happy.  It shows ya,  you can do good and make a buck at the same time.

Listen up, folks! You know how everyone's always talkin' 'bout culture? Well, lemme tell ya, it ain't just some fancy word.  It's like, the way folks do things, their beliefs, y'know?  

Now, don't go thinkin' all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are nice. That's just plain wrong!  Culture ain't a one-size-fits-all kinda thing. It's more like, understandin' why people do what they do, especially when you're tryin' to work somethin' out with 'em.

When you meet folks from a different place, it's kinda like lookin' in a mirror, seein' yourself a little bit, but different. You gotta learn their ways, like their history and what makes 'em tick.

Don't go judgin' 'em or tryin' to change 'em, just respect their ways and work with 'em.  Especially if you're the one needin' somethin' from 'em.  Treat 'em right, be polite, and you'll get further than tryin' to bulldoze your way through.

Now, culture ain't just 'bout countries, either. It's about companies too. Some places work hard, others take it easy. Some got fancy dress codes, others are more casual. It's all part of the culture.

Values are even more important, 'cause they tell you why folks do what they do. If they value respect, you gotta be respectful.  If they're all about gettin' a good deal, you gotta be ready to haggle.

So, before you sit down at the table, do your homework. Learn about the folks you're dealin' with, their culture, their values.  And remember, treat 'em right, and you'll be halfway there.

Alright, so these two fellas, St. Anselm and St. Thomas, both think God exists.  They both gotta prove it though, right? So, let's just assume they're both right about God, the God from the Bible, 'cause that's what they're talkin' about.

Now, Anselm, he's all about faith, you know? He says you gotta look inside yourself to find God. He's sayin' that since we can even think about God, He must be real. It's kinda like knowin' you need a missing piece to a puzzle, even if you can't see it yet. Anselm says God's like that missing piece, we just know He's there.

But Thomas, he's a different breed. He wants to prove God with facts, ya know, stuff you can see and touch. He says there are five good reasons why God has to exist, like how everything changes, how things have a cause, and how there are different levels of good and bad. He's sayin' it's all just plain logic, like math, that proves God is real.

So, both these guys make some good points, but neither one really nails it down for me. They both kinda take a shortcut, ya know? Anselm just assumes we know God's there, and Thomas tries to prove it with logic, but that ain't always foolproof.

So there was this prince, way back in the day, like way back, fifth or sixth century BCE,  who turned into this big deal, Buddha.  He was all about ditching the fancy life and figuring things out, and what he learned became Buddhism.  Now, this Buddhism thing, it's been around for like 2,500 years, and it ain't the same as when Buddha was kickin' around.  Take Sri Lanka, for instance, they got this water-cutting ceremony every year. Monks and regular folks do it, and it's kinda important to them, even though Buddha never mentioned nothin' about it.  See, Buddhism has changed a lot, from the little stuff to the big ideas.  All the monks and regular folks, they've had to tweak their beliefs over time.  Why? Well, things happen, both good and bad, from inside and outside the religion.

Let's get this straight, we're gonna be talkin' about "inside" and "outside," "good" and "bad," ya know, like that.  Inside stuff comes from folks who are already Buddhists, doesn't matter if they're monks or not.  Outside stuff comes from folks who ain't Buddhists.  Anything that hurts Buddhism is bad, like someone tryin' to tear it down.  And anything that doesn't really care, well, that's neutral, good or bad, depends on the outcome.

Now, let's talk about what Buddhists believe. They go for the triple gem: Buddha, the teachings, and the community.  The teachings are all in these books called the Tripitaka:  The Sutta Pitaka has Buddha's talks, the Vinaya Pitaka has the rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deep stuff about how things work. They talk about no soul (Anatta), life is suffering (Dukkha), and everything changes (Anicca).  Gotta understand these things to get outta the cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara).  And when you get outta that cycle, you get rid of desire (lobha), hate (dosa), and delusion (moha), and become enlightened.  The Vinaya Pitaka tells you how to live. Lay folks have five rules, like don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, and so on. Monks have a whole bunch more rules to follow.

The big idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering (Dukkha). Second, suffering comes from wanting things (attachment). Third, suffering can stop. Fourth, there's a way to stop suffering.

Well, lemme tell ya, the US and Mexico, they used to be at each other's throats somethin' fierce! Went on for a good 57 years, from way back in 1836 to 1893.  You know, kinda like those feuds ya hear about down south, but on a bigger scale. The biggest fight was back in 1846, the Mexican-American War.  We jumped on Mexico and took their land, Texas and the Southwest, somethin' fierce!  They had a few other run-ins along the way, but finally calmed down just before the First World War.

See, it all started because these two countries had some real differences,  like religion, culture, how things were done - you know, the usual stuff. And they both wanted the same stuff, makin' things even hotter. Kinda like how neighbors sometimes fight over the fence line.

It ain't just the US and Mexico either. Lots of countries that share a border end up buttin' heads.  They're close, which means they're always gettin' in each other's way.  Heck, some folks say the US has more problems with Mexico and Cuba than any other country in Latin America.

Religion was a big part of it too.  Back then, Americans weren't too fond of Catholics and Kings, just like they weren't too keen on Communism and Fascism later on. It was all about what ya believed and who was runnin' things. Just like how the US and Russia were at odds during the Cold War, but instead of politics, it was religion that was the main problem.  And it all went back to those old days when the English and Spanish were always fightin'.

They had a whole bunch of arguments over the years, somethin' like 17!  Most of them were about land, with people crossin' the border and causin' trouble.  Fence-mendin' time, ya know?  

But eventually, Mexico started dependin' on the US for a lot of stuff, and that kinda cooled things down.  By the late 1800s, the US was more interested in business than in taking more land, so they finally settled down.

Fifteen years ago, things went south for me. I got sick.   A real nasty one, out of nowhere.  See, I was a nurse, always dreamt of being a scientist or a writer, but everyone told me to be a nurse, said it was safe, always in demand.  So, here I was, 46, single, broke, and couldn't work.  Been on disability ever since,  15 years now.  Can't say I own much of anything.  Every day's a struggle, gotta fight for my security, for my sanity.  Nothing's certain anymore, but one thing's for sure: I couldn't have made it this far without my family and a few good friends.  When life throws you a curveball, you realize just how strong you are, or ain't.


My point is, life throws curveballs, big and small.  You can plan for some, but some things are just too big to handle alone.  Now, I get folks talkin' about smaller government, and Lord knows, it ain't exactly runnin' smooth these days. But instead of everyone building their own bunkers, I say we start trustin' each other again.  Helpin' out, ask for help when you need it.

They say America was built on rugged individualism, but that ain't the whole story.  Our forefathers got through tough times 'cause they looked out for each other, shared what they had, cared for one another.  Those pioneers crossin' the Rockies, they didn't make it alone, did they?

So, be prepared, I am. Got my disaster kit, first aid stuff, water purification tablets, even plastic sheeting for the windows if we ever get hit with somethin' nasty.  Got flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and a pantry full of canned goods.  If you got the space, grow your own food, can it, pickle it, whatever.  Wood stove's a good idea too, if you ain't livin' in an apartment.

But here's the thing:  while you're stockin' up, get to know your neighbors. That's what truly matters.

So, ya know how creatures change over time, right?  Like, why do they become the way they are?  Is there some kinda rulebook for how they gotta evolve? Back in '17, some fella named Thompson said even figuring out the simplest animal in math words was harder than it looked. And today, well, it's still tough!

But folks are tryin'.  They're usin' math to figure out how seashells, like those spiral kinda ones, grow and change over time.  They're usin' fancy computer programs and pictures of shells to see what shapes they *could* make, and then tryin' to figure out how those shapes actually happened in real life.

Think of a seashell like a little tube windin' around and around. Each loop is called a whorl, and they all go around a center line called the columella.  

These whorls can get bigger or smaller, and there's a line called a suture between each one.  Usually, the biggest whorl is the last one, and all the rest are called the spire.  The pointy end of the spire is the apex, and the other end, well, that's the base.  And there's a hole called the aperture where the critter lives.

So, these scientists are tryin' to figure out how all these parts work together to make a shell, and how they change over time. They're usin' math to see what's possible and then tryin' to figure out how those possibilities come true in nature.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin' about these numbers in Indonesia.  

For the last ten years, babies ain't been doin' so hot.  They ain't dyin' off at a crazy rate, but they ain't gettin' any healthier neither.  Indonesia's doin' okay on some stuff, like gettin' clean water and toilets, but when it comes to moms and babies, they ain't doin' so hot.  They gotta step it up if they wanna meet their goals by 2015.

See, they're sayin' more babies are bein' born with a doctor or midwife around, which sounds good, right?  Well, not so fast.  A lot of these midwives ain't really trained to handle anythin' serious, so when somethin' goes wrong, well, it ain't good.  That's why so many moms are dyin' from bleedin' out.  

And here's another thing: less kids are gettin' help when they're sick, especially with the tummy bugs.  And what about after the baby's born?  Nobody's really keepin' track of that, but it ain't lookin' good.  

They ain't doin' enough cesarean sections either.  Only 4% of the time.  Now, in the cities, it's 7%, but in the country, it's only 2%.  That tells ya somethin', don't it?  Healthcare ain't reachin' everyone.  It's like the rich folks get all the good stuff and the poor folks are left behind.

So, what's the answer?  Should they just focus on fixin' one problem at a time, or should they just make the whole healthcare system better?  Well, it's a tough call.  

Program-specific stuff sounds good, cuz it's easier to see what's workin' and what ain't.  But you know what? Sometimes that means they'll forget about other stuff and everyone'll be tryin' to grab money for their own program.  Plus, it gets confusing with so many different programs doin' the same thing.

Alright, listen up. These fancy Victorian books, they're all about the little details and the rich folks back in the day. But then you got these two, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," they're different kinda beasts. They're like, "Let's throw in some mystery and some crazy stuff," ya know?  It ain't your typical Victorian novel.  This mystery stuff, it makes the characters come alive, ya see? It shows you what they're really thinkin' and feelin'. 

Take this part from "Oliver Twist," for instance:

“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)


These books use mystery, like dreams or somethin', to show you what's goin' on inside their characters.  Like with Oliver, these weird happenings, they show ya what's botherin' him, what he's really seein' in this messed up world. When they finally revisit the shootin' of Oliver, he relives it in his head, like a bad dream. He's tryin' to find help, but it's like he's stuck, ya know? The passage shows how Oliver's got no control over nothin'. He's in bad shape, seein' things, and these hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit are just makin' it worse.  The shootin' just overwhelms him. He can't even feel the pain, it's constant. It's all just fear now. You gotta wonder who's really behind all this bad luck, 'cause it ain't Oliver. This shootin' shows how powerless Oliver really is. He can't even try to stop it, not even when his life is on the line. It's like Old Fagin's broken him, made him give up, ya know?

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."

A couple years back, I was workin' at this after-school program, helpin' out those little rugrats with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so I mostly helped out with those. This one kid, Adrian, maybe third or fourth grade, was givin' me fits.  Seemed like he couldn't read worth a lick. He'd nail some words, then totally botch others, real strange. Now, I knew he was Latino, and he spoke perfect English, so it was confusing as heck. 

We were strugglin' to get anywhere when his momma came in one day. Now, she didn't speak a lick of English, only Spanish.  Me, I was just learnin' a few words myself, but we managed to communicate somehow. And then it hit me, like a ton of bricks! Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet that well.  

I don't know if that helped him much, but I hope he's doin' better now. 

That's why I'm talkin' about this language barrier in schools, especially here in California. It ain't always as obvious as ya think. Even if a kid speaks English, readin' it can still be a real struggle. 

We all know this problem exists, so what do we do about it? For Adrian, it was simple:  help him with the English alphabet and pronunciation. But for kids who barely speak English, it's way more complicated. Ain't no one-size-fits-all answer.  Dual language programs,  immersion, private tutors, ESL classes, none of it works solo. We gotta combine 'em all!

First off, dual language programs are a good idea, not just for Spanish speakers, but for everyone. You know, kids in those programs do better in school. Some folks are scared, thinkin' it's a waste of money, but that ain't true. 

If we made these programs the norm instead of the exception, everyone would benefit. But how do we do it? We can't make every teacher bilingual, that's crazy talk. But we can have bilingual aides, tutors, whatever ya wanna call 'em, to help out.

Listen, you ever think about why we're all here? I mean, what's the big picture?  Some folks, they go to church or temple, or just try to figure it out on their own.  A lot of us just go along with what our folks taught us, but some, well, they say "Nah, ain't nothin' out there but what we can see." They live for themselves, just their own world, ya know?  And sometimes folks change their minds about all that, what they believe.  No matter what, we're all searchin', tryin' to make sense of it all. We're lookin' for somethin' to guide us, somethin' bigger than ourselves.

My old man, he always liked cardinals. We were sittin' on the porch, rain hammerin' down, smokin' cigarettes. The gutters were overflowin', and the plants were gettin' soaked. He was lookin' out at the rain, like he was thinkin' about somethin' far away. He'd gotten thinner, his clothes baggy, and his hair was gettin' sparse. He didn't look at me much, just kept starin' at that rain. I felt lost, scared, but I couldn't bring myself to talk about missin' him. It would just make it too real.  So I hugged him, sat back down, and just watched the rain with him.

He kicked the bucket that December, just five days after I turned 22. The chemo and radiation kept him alive longer than the doctors thought, but it didn't stop the pain. I couldn't figure out what good it did.  If there's a God out there, I thought, he ain't listenin' to me anymore.

I didn't wanna watch him die. I just couldn't. I wanted to remember him how he was, not how he went. Besides, I knew him better than anyone else. I knew he wouldn't want me there watchin' him fade away. So I hid in my bed for three days, waitin' for the news.

Nobody even called.

Alright, so this "Gothic Novel" thing, it's a real head-scratcher, kinda like when you try to figure out what your Uncle Bubba's talkin' about. This Ian Watt fella, he calls it an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" which means it's both old and new at the same time.  People have been trashin' it, praisin' it, sayin' it's got no depth, then turnin' around and sayin' it's got this "terrible sublime" thing goin' on.  That's what Burke said, anyway.  See, this first "Gothic Novel," "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, it took bits and pieces from those ol' romances and those newfangled novels and mixed 'em together. He called it a "Gothic Story." Kinda like how I like to mix up a good ol' fashioned whiskey with a splash of somethin' sweet.

Walpole, he used all this stuff from old theater and tried to make it fit with the new way of writin' novels. He wanted people to get inside the characters' heads, you know? That's what makes Gothic novels stick around so long, even though they're old as dirt. It's like wearin' your grandpa's boots - they're old, but they still work!

One of the big things in Gothic novels is this "Chivalry" thing. Back in the day, they had these knights, all brave and honorable, and that's what folks were tryin' to be like. But these writers, like Walpole, they thought folks weren't so chivalrous anymore. So they wrote about these knights to make folks remember what they'd lost.

Walpole, he was worried about the world back then, there was a lot of trouble goin' on. Maybe he thought folks had forgotten how to be good, you know? He put that idea into his stories, especially in this character, Frederic. This Frederic fella, he was like a knight outta a fairytale: he was a prince, he'd been through some bad stuff, and everyone thought he was dead.  He's like the poster boy for chivalry, but maybe a little too perfect, kinda like that guy at the gym who's always showin' off.

Alright, so let me tell ya 'bout this thing called supply chain management.  It's like, how ya get stuff from when someone wants it, all the way back to where it started, you know?  This fella, Keith Oliver, came up with the name back in '82. He figured out it's all 'bout makin' sure you get what folks want, fast and cheap.  

Now, there's six big parts to this whole shebang: makin' the stuff, gettin' the stuff, keepin' track of the stuff, knowin' where the stuff is, movin' the stuff, and talkin' 'bout the stuff.  Basically, you gotta do all these things right to keep your customers happy.

First off, ya gotta make the stuff. That's the heart of it all.  Gotta figure out what folks want, when they want it, how much they want, and where to make it.  You gotta watch the market, see what people are buyin', and then decide what to build.  Like, if everyone's buyin' red pickup trucks, ya better be makin' red pickup trucks!  

Then ya gotta figure out where to build 'em.  You gotta think about the best place to make the stuff,  keepin' in mind how much it costs and how good it has to be.  After that, ya gotta make a plan for makin' the stuff, makin' sure the machines are workin' right and the workers know what they're doin'.

Next up is gettin' all the parts you need.  You might have different places makin' different parts, like one place for the engines and another for the seats.  Ya gotta make sure all those parts get to the right place at the right time.  Sometimes, ya might even outsource some stuff to other companies.  That's just a fancy way of sayin' ya hire someone else to make somethin' for ya.  It's like when ya take ya car to the mechanic, ya ain't makin' the car yourself, ya just gettin' someone else to do it.

Duke Ellington, he was a real piano man, and he knew how to make his band sound good. He wasn't always the flashiest player, but he sure knew how to write tunes that showed off his guys. Ellington, he'd set up these frameworks where a musician could really let loose and improvise, and he'd also write these tight, orchestrated parts that made each guy in the band sound their best. It was like he knew exactly what made each guy tick, ya know?  He built this sound, this whole vibe, that was all his own.  People say his stuff was some of the most original and brilliant jazz ever made.
This dictionary, the Grove Music one, they say Ellington was always usin' the voice as an instrument. This song, "Creole Love Call", it shows what he meant. He used the voice to add this texture and color, without all the fuss of words. And it showed how he could make his soloists shine.  This slow blues song, it's got these six different parts, each one different and special.


The first part, it's like a conversation between the voice and the woodwinds, starts smooth, then gets rougher.  The second part, a trumpet solo, playin' muted,  stretchin' out the melody and addin' these bluesy notes.   The third part, the clarinet takes over, playin' high and sweet, with the piano doin' this subtle, syncopated thing in the background.  The fourth part, the whole band chimes in, like a call and response between the brass and the woodwinds.  The fifth part, that's the big one, the woodwinds callin' and respondin' high and bright, with the brass and rhythm section doin' this stop-time thing, like a heartbeat. Then the last part, it goes back to the first part, the voice and the woodwinds talkin' again, but this time the voice gets all raspy, like it's singin' on its own.  Then there's a little tag at the end, a vocal run and a trombone playin' somethin' kinda dissonant, just for fun.

Ellington usin' the voice like that, it's like he was colorin' the whole song.  And this was just one of the things he did. In another song, "Hot and Bothered", he takes this muted trumpet player, "Bubber" Miley, and this scat singer, Baby Cox, and he makes 'em sound like they're talkin' to each other. It's like the trumpet is singin' and the voice is playin' an instrument.  He did the same thing in "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)", usin' this trombone player, Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, to start the melody in a way that was just perfect.

She always felt like somethin' was missin', you know? Like there was a hole in her life that nothin' could fill. It started when she was about 14, just gettin' into that teenage thing, and it was still there three years later, when she was 17. By then, she figured out she wanted someone, not some shiny new thing. But she just wasn't feelin' it for any boys. Some fellas tried to woo her, all awkward and shy, but nothin' ever clicked. She'd wrack her brain, tryin' to figure out why she felt this way, a plain ol' teenage girl with no interest in fellas.  She had a few theories, but nothin' stuck. So she just kept livin', always wonderin' about this feelin' inside her. 

Now, her folks were good people, calm and quiet. They never fought, and she hardly ever got in trouble with 'em. The only time they butted heads was when she tried to act like she was all grown up. She was a sweet kid, but she had a big, boisterous personality that stood out against her parents' laid-back vibes. It made her likeable, though. Everyone liked her.

This day, though, wasn't one of those calm days. She was moseyin' around the house, lookin' for somethin' to get her goin', when she heard a yelp from the kitchen. It was her mama, and she sounded hurt. She ran in, panickin', "Mom! What's wrong?!" Her mama was sprawled on the floor, grimachin' and sayin' "Ow" between breaths.  She rushed over and put her hand on her mama, tryin' to help. "Ouch... sweety, I... need you to take me to... the hospital."

Her words were choked out, and her daughter knew it was bad. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where to meet you." Her mama pointed, and her daughter, glad she'd taken those self-defense classes, scooped her mama up and carried her to the car. She laid her down in the back seat and drove like a bat outta hell.

The hospital smelled like sickness and fear, but she didn't notice. She was too busy lookin' after her mama. She rushed her in, yellin' for help. A bunch of doctors gathered around, and someone wheeled her mama to a bed. They took her away, and her daughter sat there, worry gnawin' at her gut.


Turns out, her mama had fallen off a step stool reachin' for somethin' up high.

So, listen up!  This here study wanted to see if eatin' like folks in the Mediterranean, we're talkin' the "aMed diet," would keep ya heart healthy and keep ya from havin' a stroke.  Now, this "aMed diet" is like a fancy way of sayin' eat yer fruits, veggies, nuts, and fish, and cut back on the meat and greasy stuff. A little wine's okay too, just don't go overboard. 

See, they done some studies before, and they found that folks who ate like this were less likely to die from heart problems.  They even did a test where they told folks to eat this way, and they lost weight and their cholesterol got better.  But nobody really looked at strokes before.

So, they got 74,886 women, good lookin' nurses mostly, ages 38 to 63, and asked 'em what they ate for 20 years. They gave these ladies these fancy questionaires,  like "How much broccoli ya eatin'?"  They even checked their records to make sure they were tellin' the truth.  They also looked at how much they smoked, if they took vitamins, and if they were usin' hormone stuff after menopause.  

They figured out that the women who ate more like folks in the Mediterranean were less likely to have a heart attack or a stroke.  Out of all the ladies, 2391 had a heart attack, 1763 had a stroke, and 1077 died from heart problems. The ladies who ate the best were 29% less likely to have a heart attack or stroke.

Well, lemme tell ya, back in '07, this whole country went belly up. Jobs were scarcer than hen's teeth, houses were worth nothin', and even big ol' companies went bust. And guess what? This mess ain't over yet! We gotta figure out what went wrong and how to stop this whole dang train wreck.

See, it all started with these slick politicians makin' decisions that were about as smart as a possum in a rainstorm. They pressured banks and businesses to give out loans to folks who couldn't afford 'em. It was like pourin' gasoline on a fire, and the whole thing went up in smoke!

Now, there's these fancy organizations called Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac. They were supposed to help folks buy homes, but they were gettin' pressured to buy up all these bad loans, pack 'em up like Christmas presents, and sell 'em off to everyone. When folks stopped payin' their mortgages, the whole house of cards came tumblin' down.

This whole mess started back in the Clinton days. He was tryin' to get re-elected, so he made it easier for folks to get loans, even if they weren't exactly financially stable. Some folks, like this fella Steven Holmes from the New York Times, saw the writing on the wall and warned about what could happen. But nobody listened.

And let me tell ya, these newfangled mortgages were somethin' else. They had all these fancy names like "adjustable-rate mortgages" and "collateralized debt obligations."  It was like a big ol' tangled mess, and nobody really understood how it all worked.

All those fancy financial games left folks with more debt than they could handle. And when the housing bubble burst, it was like a bomb goin' off in the economy. Big banks like Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers went kaput, and even Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to change their tune. Fannie and Freddie were in deep trouble too, and the government had to step in and bail 'em out.

Listen up, writers! We all know the golden rule: "Show, don't tell." But sometimes, even the best of us get caught up in the weeds and end up with too much talkin' and not enough action. That's where exposition comes in—the part of the story where you dump a whole bucket of information on the reader. It's like watching someone tell you a story while they monopolize the entire conversation. 

Think of it like this:  You're reading a story and the author goes on and on about how the main character met her hubby, got hitched in a big ol' shindig, and then BAM! He gets whacked right in front of her eyes. Now, nobody wants to read two pages of that, with characters talking like robots and not showing any real emotion. 

Instead, the author should give us some juicy details about this hubby fella. Let us see how much he loved his wife through his words and actions. Show us how she changed and grew because of him. Get us invested in his story so that when he meets his maker, we feel the pain along with her.  

We want the story to have some meat on its bones! We want to be drawn in and feel like we're right there in the middle of it all.

Brothers, they're somethin' else, ain't they?  Like nothin' else in the world, ya know?  Love 'em, hate 'em, get mad at 'em, but they're always there.  They see right through ya, like lookin' in a mirror.  Sometimes that's good, sometimes it's real bad.   Like,  brothers understand each other, more than anyone else. They see themselves in each other, good and bad.  When things get rough, that's when ya really see what kinda bond they got.  It can be powerful, strong as hell, but it can also hurt like crazy. 

This book, "The Scarlet Ibis", it talks about that bond,  the good and the bad.  Two brothers, settin' out on this crazy journey, and it all goes south.   One brother, he's got this pride thing goin' on, thinks he's better than the other.  It's like he wants this perfect brother, someone to match him, ya know?  But the other brother, he's different.  He can't keep up, can't do all the things the older brother wants to do.  They're both different, they both got somethin' to learn.  The story shows how pride can hurt, how it can lead to bad decisions.  It's a tough read, but it makes ya think, ya know?

Y'all listen up, cuz this brain thing is a real head scratcher, kinda like tryin' to figure out what my brother was talkin' about after a night out dancin'. 

See, back in the day, folks thought the brain was like a wax tablet, ya know, somethin' ya could write on and wipe clean. Then it was like papyrus, like them old scrolls. Then folks got fancy and said it was like a book. Now, these brainy scientists, they say it's like a computer. But lemme tell ya, all these comparisons, they ain't always right.

So, you gotta understand, this brain of ours, it's like a big ol' factory, takin' in all sorts of stuff. You see somethin', hear somethin', feel somethin', all that gets turned into signals, like little messages. Then, your brain, it's like a master chef, takin' those messages and cookin' up somethin' outta them. It's a two-way street, too. It's like, sometimes your brain uses what it already knows to figure things out faster, kinda like when you see a box and you know right away what it is.

And then there's this thing called attention, it's like a bouncer at a club, choosin' what gets in and what gets tossed out. Your brain's got so much goin' on, it can't pay attention to everything. It's like, you see a million blades of grass, but you don't really notice each one. But if someone says your name, bam! You hear it clear as day.

Now, your brain, it's gotta store all this information, like a giant library. There's different kinds of memory, short-term, long-term, all sorts of things. It's like, you hear somethin', you gotta hold onto it for a bit, then maybe tuck it away for later. And how it all gets organized, well, that's a whole other story, like tryin' to figure out the whole damn Dewey Decimal System.

Listen up, folks! This here Huxley fella, he's got somethin' to say about all this fancy newfangled technology and the way the money folks run things. See, in his book, "Brave New World," folks are all about lookin' out for each other, but they ain't thinkin' for themselves none. They're all about havin' a good time right now, no matter what.  

It's like they're puppets, y'know?  This big boss man, the World Controller, he's pullin' all the strings.  And Huxley, he's sayin' this whole thing is gonna mess us up somethin' fierce.  He's talkin' about how the rich folks are keepin' the poor folks in the dark, makin' them think they're better off than they really are.  He sees right through it, just like I see through a politician's promises.  It's all smoke and mirrors, folks.  

He calls it "false consciousness," like they're dreamin' a dream they think is real.  But the truth is, they're gettin' used, used like a cheap tool.  They're buyin' into a system that ain't doin' nothin' but line the pockets of the fat cats.   

And these folks, they ain't even thinkin' 'bout it.  They're too busy chasin' after the next shiny thing, the next pleasure.  They don't even know how to feel real emotions anymore, let alone fight back.   

It's a sad state of affairs, folks.  And Huxley, he's tryin' to wake us up.  He's sayin' we gotta start thinkin' for ourselves, gotta see through the lies.   We gotta fight for our freedom, or we're gonna end up livin' in a world where we're nothin' but cogs in a machine.

Well, lemme tell ya, this here Uni Park's a right pain in the neck to get around, especially if ya live like me, way out East Halls, where the sun don't shine and the wind blows hard enough to blow ya off your feet.  It's a good thing I ain't got to walk all the way to Willard Buildin' - that's like walkin' from here to Dallas!  Used to be, there was nothin' out there but open fields, but now they're buildin' all sorts of fancy stuff - sports fields, new buildings, even apartments.  Makes ya wonder what's next, a dang rodeo?  Point is, this place keeps gettin' bigger, and harder to navigate.  

Now, I reckon the best way to get around this campus is on a dang bicycle.  But a bicycle ain't gonna do ya no good if nobody's ridin' it, and the campus ain't built for bikes.  

I was talkin' to my buddy the other day, and he said he'd been ridin' again after takin' a break for a few years.  He said, "Man, why'd I ever stop?  Bikes are the only way to get around these parts."  He's right, ya know?  Besides bein' good for ya, they're the fastest way to get from Point A to Point B.  I ain't talkin' 'bout no fancy mountain bike, just a regular ol' bike, and a bowl of grits for breakfast will get ya goin' for 30 miles or more.

I live off campus now, just as far from the center of campus as some of those dorms.  Best thing I did this year was buy a bike.  Used to take me a good 25 minutes to walk to my class in Thomas Buildin'.  Now, whiz on over there in 5 minutes flat if I pedal like the wind.  The only problem is, Pollock Road ain't always the friendliest place for a bike.

Walkin' ain't bad, but I ain't got time for it.  Without my bike, I'd be walkin' to class every day, and that's a whole lotta time wasted.  Think about it, over 2 1/2 hours a week just walkin' to class.  Add that to walkin' to other places, and I ain't got no time for nothin' else.
